# Ship changes: sync → commit → sync → push → sync → Firebase deploy

For this repo's **Firebase Hosting** (`web/`) and **Cloud Functions** (`functions/`), the ordered shipping ritual is:

> **`git fetch` is not `git pull`.** `git fetch origin` only refreshes `refs/remotes/origin/*`; it does NOT advance your local `main` or your working tree. At every sync step below: run `git fetch origin`, read `git status`, and **only if status reports `behind by N commits`** run `git pull --ff-only origin main` (or `git pull --rebase origin main` on a feature branch). Local `main` is "up to date" only when `git status` reports `Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main'`.

## 1. Sync (start)

```bash
git fetch origin && git status        # MUST report "up to date with 'origin/main'"
# If status reports "behind by N commits":
git pull --ff-only origin main        # advances local main to match origin/main
git status                            # re-verify it now reports "up to date" before editing
```

## 2. Commit

```bash
git status                            # review focused scope
git add <focused paths>
git commit -m "[<github-handle>] …"   # e.g. [apalmer] — see CONTRIBUTING.md § commit prefix
```

## 3. Sync again — IMMEDIATELY before push

```bash
git fetch origin && git status        # MUST report "up to date" (or "ahead by N" — both mean local matches origin/main as a base)
# If now behind or diverged:
git pull --rebase origin main         # re-run verifiers/tests if the rebase invalidated them
git status                            # re-verify before pushing
```

## 4. Push

```bash
git push origin <current-branch>
```

## 5. Pre-deploy verifier (only when `web/profile-viewer/` changed)

```bash
npm run verify:profile-viewer-routes
```

Guards `journey-arbitration.html` redirect, `journey-arbitration-v2`, `eds-quickstart`. Also asserts `decisioning-overview-v2.html` is hard-deleted (forbidden file).

## 6. Sync again — IMMEDIATELY before Firebase deploy

This is **the most often forgotten** step. `firebase deploy --only hosting` ships whatever is on YOUR local disk under `web/`, NOT what is on `origin/main`. If a teammate pushed between step 4 and step 6, you will silently overwrite their hosted assets.

```bash
git fetch origin && git status        # MUST report "up to date with 'origin/main'"
# If status reports "behind", local working tree does NOT yet match GitHub:
git pull --ff-only origin main
git status                            # re-verify it now reports "up to date" before deploying
# AND rebuild any vendored sub-apps so the deploy carries their pulled source:
npm run build:edp                     # if their commit touched experience-decisioning-playground/
npm run build:eds-quickstart          # if their commit touched the eds-quickstart submodule pointer
```

## 7. Deploy

```bash
npx -y firebase-tools@latest deploy --only functions,hosting
# or scoped:
npx -y firebase-tools@latest deploy --only hosting
npx -y firebase-tools@latest deploy --only functions
```

## Hard rules

- **Do not deploy without committing.** If the user explicitly asks for Git-only or local-only, skip deploy and say so.
- **Do not skip step 6.** "I already fetched at step 3" is not sufficient — minutes pass between push and deploy and that is enough for a teammate's commit to land.
- **Do not run `firebase deploy` while behind `origin/main`.** Always `git pull --ff-only` first, then rebuild any sub-apps, then deploy.
- See companion rule `sync-origin-main.mdc` for the full three-checkpoint pull discipline.

Aligns with `CONTRIBUTING.md` (deploy after tracked commits). CI does not auto-deploy functions/hosting.
